01:03.104 --> 01:04.706
I am frozen.

01:04.809 --> 01:07.902
I think it's gonna snow.

01:08.008 --> 01:09.703
How did we buy all this
in one trip?

01:09.807 --> 01:11.102
Whoo! Teamwork.

01:11.208 --> 01:12.900
I don't even remember
what we bought.

01:13.007 --> 01:15.003
Oh. I just hope you don't remember
what we spent.

01:15.105 --> 01:18.102
That I'm gonna remember
for the rest of my life.

01:18.205 --> 01:21.102
Oh, my gosh. I'm just glad
that it's over.

01:21.207 --> 01:23.502
Oh. Um, actually, it's not.

01:23.606 --> 01:25.201
The groceries are in the back.

01:25.308 --> 01:26.702
I knew that.

01:26.806 --> 01:27.600
You want my help?

01:27.707 --> 01:28.903
No, but I could use a drink.

01:29.005 --> 01:31.101
- Oh. Something hot?
- Uh, not for the cold.

01:31.207 --> 01:32.802
For the bills.

01:32.907 --> 01:35.302
Right.

02:21.806 --> 02:24.401
It's raining outside.
Can you believe this?

02:24.508 --> 02:27.502
Is this a mosquito?

02:27.605 --> 02:30.703
This time of year?

02:31.606 --> 02:32.801
Wow. All right.

02:32.905 --> 02:34.903
Global warming has come to Grandview at...

02:35.006 --> 02:37.501
9:53 P.M.

02:39.606 --> 02:41.803
You ok?

02:41.906 --> 02:47.003
I just feel hot all the sudden.
I'm gonna go change.

02:48.007 --> 02:51.403
Yeah. That's a mosquito.

04:42.406 --> 04:45.803
EPISODE 2x11
Cat's Claw

04:48.406 --> 04:51.100
All I did was walk into our room,
and all of the sudden,

04:51.205 --> 04:55.101
I was in the middle of a jungle
with vines and yellow flowers.

04:55.207 --> 04:58.201
It was raining, and there were
bugs crawling all over my feet.

04:58.305 --> 04:59.803
I mean, it was awful.

04:59.908 --> 05:01.102
Maybe it was something you ate.

05:01.208 --> 05:02.701
We were at the same restaurant.

05:02.806 --> 05:04.503
Yes, but did not have
the spicy egg roll.

05:04.607 --> 05:09.203
Yeah. It was not the egg roll,
and I know a ghost when I see one.

05:09.307 --> 05:11.702
Or a ghost's hands
when I see one.

05:11.805 --> 05:13.703
Have a little ice cream,

05:13.807 --> 05:15.201
help cool you down.

05:15.306 --> 05:17.801
What I want to know is
how a ghost from the jungle

05:17.906 --> 05:18.903
made it into our house.

05:19.007 --> 05:23.002
The closest I've been to a jungle is
the Central Park Zoo, and I was 10.

05:23.108 --> 05:24.702
Hey. Maybe you brought him
back from the mall.

05:24.806 --> 05:28.300
Well, it doesn't matter now
that he knows where I live.

05:28.406 --> 05:30.602
I just hope he's done with me
for the night.

05:30.705 --> 05:33.503
Yeah. Me, too.

05:33.907 --> 05:37.203
Man, it's coming down.

05:37.906 --> 05:40.102
Jim.

05:50.505 --> 05:51.602
Morning!

05:51.708 --> 05:52.203
Good morning!

05:52.307 --> 05:53.901
Hey. I think I struck gold,

05:54.005 --> 05:56.801
but I'm gonna need some help
carrying everything in, ok?

05:56.907 --> 05:59.903
I have a friend who just bought a house
out of probate about a month ago,

06:00.007 --> 06:03.203
and apparently, there was a little old
lady who lived in it her whole life,

06:03.308 --> 06:05.602
so she got everything
in the house, as well.

06:05.708 --> 06:08.403
I guess there was a whole bunch
of great stuff in the attic,

06:08.507 --> 06:09.803
and she knew we worked together,

06:09.907 --> 06:13.603
and she wanted to know if we were
interested in consigning any of it,

06:13.707 --> 06:16.603
so I brought a few things down.

06:16.708 --> 06:19.303
This stuff is in amazingly good shape.

06:19.407 --> 06:21.101
I don't know what it is, but I like it.

06:21.207 --> 06:22.500
It's a sextant.

06:22.606 --> 06:24.500
No  kidding.
That's what they call that?

06:24.607 --> 06:26.501
I don't kid about sextants.

06:26.607 --> 06:28.403
Hey. I love this.

06:28.505 --> 06:31.601
See, that is definitely you.
You look great in that!

06:31.708 --> 06:34.803
Don't I have to be
a tap-dancer to wear this?

06:34.908 --> 06:37.900
Ohh! This is beautiful.

06:38.006 --> 06:39.603
This...

06:39.707 --> 06:42.701
is definitely me.

06:42.906 --> 06:45.000
She's mine.

06:45.107 --> 06:47.203
Take it off!

06:47.306 --> 06:48.803
Something wrong?

06:48.908 --> 06:52.002
- I thought I saw a spider on it.
- Oh, god! Really? Was it big?

06:52.108 --> 06:53.003
Big one.

06:53.107 --> 06:55.003
Oh. Well, ok.

06:55.107 --> 06:57.002
No more old hats for me.

06:57.108 --> 06:58.702
You know what?

06:58.808 --> 07:01.501
Um, I have a quick errand to run.
You good here?

07:01.605 --> 07:02.402
Yeah. Sure.

07:02.505 --> 07:08.302
I just want to get this dry-cleaned
before we put it on display.

07:08.508 --> 07:11.002
Oh, god!

07:11.207 --> 07:14.403
Ugh! I hate spiders.

07:25.107 --> 07:27.101
Damn it!

07:27.208 --> 07:29.400
Oh, damn it!

07:29.508 --> 07:32.000
Damn it!

07:32.408 --> 07:34.902
How long have you been standing there?
You know what? It doesn't matter.

07:35.005 --> 07:40.502
I don't have time. I have a meeting in
15 minutes, and I can't find my keys,
so make it snappy.

07:40.606 --> 07:43.101
I did not leave my keys there.

07:43.205 --> 07:45.300
Ok. Well, I've only got
15 minutes, so...

07:45.406 --> 07:49.400
No. I didn't leave my keys in the door.
I never leave my keys in the door.

07:49.508 --> 07:52.500
- This is--this is really strange.
- Everyone loses their keys.

07:52.606 --> 07:54.403
I'm not everyone, and I don't
leave my keys in the door.

07:54.506 --> 07:57.300
That's what I'm trying to explain
to you. This is... this...

07:57.408 --> 07:58.701
is that a cake?

07:58.808 --> 08:00.103
No.

08:00.207 --> 08:02.500
Recognize this?

08:02.606 --> 08:06.402
Oh, my god.

08:06.408 --> 08:08.103
What?

08:08.208 --> 08:10.203
It's a hat.

08:10.305 --> 08:12.401
It's a nice one, too.
I'd say 1940?

08:12.508 --> 08:13.501
How much do you want for it?

08:13.606 --> 08:15.301
That's not why I brought it.

08:15.407 --> 08:16.300
As if I didn't know.

08:16.407 --> 08:17.501
No!

08:17.608 --> 08:19.301
What are we afraid of?

08:19.407 --> 08:21.401
- I think it might be Romano's.
- Who's Romano?

08:21.507 --> 08:24.200
- The cult leader. The one that you...
- Oh, yeah. Him.

08:24.305 --> 08:26.203
You really thought
it belonged to him, huh?

08:26.308 --> 08:29.102
You brought this to me, so...

08:29.206 --> 08:31.402
So I could tell you if
it meant anything terrible?

08:31.508 --> 08:33.802
Well, aside from messing up my hair
and giving me headaches,

08:33.905 --> 08:35.501
- hats don't really mean much...
- What's this?

08:35.605 --> 08:39.503
Careful!
Don't knock that over.

08:40.806 --> 08:42.903
Congratulations, Melinda.
You just saved a life.

08:43.005 --> 08:44.400
- Excuse me?
- It's a manikin.

08:44.507 --> 08:47.503
It's used to treat sickness by 
a shaman, medicine man, witch doctor,

08:47.608 --> 08:48.900
whatever you want to call it.

08:49.008 --> 08:52.900
It's placed near a patient, and an
incantation is given by Mr Hocus Pocus.

08:53.008 --> 08:56.500
If this wooden figure is to remain
upright during said incantation,

08:56.607 --> 08:59.603
then the patient will live.
They'll recover, but if during

08:59.708 --> 09:03.102
said incantation this
were to fall down...

09:03.207 --> 09:08.103
that would mean impending death
or severe drunkenness.

09:08.205 --> 09:11.403
- I think I've seen this.
- Really? Where?

09:11.507 --> 09:13.801
A  museum, I think.
Where'd you get it?

09:13.908 --> 09:16.701
That was given to me by a member
of the Machiguenga tribe,

09:16.808 --> 09:19.401
which  I almost died getting it,
and that's a different story.

09:19.507 --> 09:22.501
Look. I have...
I have really got to go.

09:22.605 --> 09:24.402
I thought you said
that I had 15 minutes.

09:24.606 --> 09:26.403
You're on Payne time, baby.

09:26.507 --> 09:28.001
Professor Payne!

09:28.107 --> 09:29.600
I was 3 weeks in Peru.

09:29.706 --> 09:33.800
I was documenting native cultural
traditions for my beloved university.

09:33.903 --> 09:37.507
Religious, tribal, symbols,
belief systems, et cetera,

09:37.606 --> 09:40.205
and I came across this practice
called kanaima.

09:40.304 --> 09:45.706
It's the mutilation and killing of
enemies and then the consumption
of a rather awful concoction.

09:45.809 --> 09:48.302
Smells terrible, and it's made up
of putrefied human remains,

09:48.406 --> 09:51.903
which I accidentally almost ingested.
At least, I think it was accidental.

09:52.008 --> 09:53.802
I prefer to think that they were
trying to assassinate me.

09:53.906 --> 09:57.003
It makes for a much more
compelling story. Excuse me.

09:57.105 --> 09:58.701
- Can I just ask you...
- No. You know what?

09:58.806 --> 10:00.803
This I should really...

10:00.906 --> 10:03.700
do by myself.

10:59.805 --> 11:02.503
Are you ok?

11:03.208 --> 11:05.902
Are you ok?

11:12.405 --> 11:14.601
And then I turn around, and I am
back in the forest again,

11:14.708 --> 11:18.700
and this manikin falls
right on top of me.

11:18.807 --> 11:19.502
A mannequin.

11:19.607 --> 11:22.800
And not one of those James Perse
kind of mannequins in the window
at Neiman Marcus.

11:22.906 --> 11:27.102
I'm talking about the kind
of manikin that witch doctors
use to treat sick people.

11:27.205 --> 11:29.003
Did the ghost tell you that?

11:29.107 --> 11:32.203
No. Professor Payne,
anyway, all I know

11:32.308 --> 11:34.801
is that if it falls over
someone will die.

11:34.907 --> 11:36.801
- Seems like somebody already did.
- No. Not the ghost.

11:36.906 --> 11:38.001
Somebody's going to die.

11:38.108 --> 11:39.402
Hey. You know what
I can't figure?

11:39.507 --> 11:42.401
How is it that the ghost of someone
who died in the jungle

11:42.505 --> 11:43.702
ends up in Grandview?

11:43.808 --> 11:45.500
I mean, the jungle's not
exactly down the block.

11:45.607 --> 11:47.303
You know, maybe it was Payne.

11:47.406 --> 11:49.101
He said he was in Peru.

11:49.208 --> 11:51.002
Peru has jungle?

11:51.105 --> 11:56.003
Yeah. And he does have
the carving in his office.

11:56.105 --> 11:57.502
Maybe it's attached to Payne, huh?

11:57.607 --> 11:59.500
I mean, is that where you saw
the ghost, in Payne's office?

11:59.608 --> 12:01.903
No. Down the hall
near the men's restroom.

12:02.008 --> 12:04.303
The ghost is haunting the men's
restroom? That's disgusting.

12:04.408 --> 12:08.100
No. Payne was in the restroom,
and the ghost was behind me.

12:08.207 --> 12:12.101
Either the ghost followed you,
or it was on campus.

12:12.206 --> 12:13.302
You know, maybe he was student.

12:13.406 --> 12:15.900
Whatever happened to him,
it was really unpleasant.

12:16.008 --> 12:17.603
I mean, every time
he tries to talk,

12:17.706 --> 12:21.401
it's just all this blood just
running out of his mouth and...

12:21.507 --> 12:22.502
Hey.

12:22.606 --> 12:25.103
Oh. Sorry.

12:25.205 --> 12:27.600
Hey! This is where I was.

12:27.706 --> 12:30.002
Look!

12:31.508 --> 12:32.702
Definitely not Grandview.

12:32.805 --> 12:36.201
No. That is the plant.
That's the thing that the ghost
was holding that cut my hand.

12:36.305 --> 12:38.403
- Una de Gato?
- Yeah. Cat's Claw.

12:38.506 --> 12:40.301
It's from the rain forest in South America.

12:40.406 --> 12:44.102
"Being studied as a medicinal treatment
for dengue fever, yellow fever, and ebola."

12:44.207 --> 12:46.703
Wow! Those are really the big ones.

12:46.806 --> 12:49.402
You know what? If he caught one of these,
that explains the blood in the mouth.

12:49.505 --> 12:51.600
- They can cause internal hemorrhaging.
- Hey! Listen to this.

12:51.705 --> 12:55.803
"Dr. Penn Grogan, one of the experts
on tropical medicinal plant research

12:55.907 --> 13:00.302
brought back these specimens from
the Rockland university research
expedition last summer. "

13:00.407 --> 13:02.602
Bingo.

13:02.705 --> 13:10.401
You know, why do I have a really
sinking feeling I know where you're
gonna be tomorrow morning?

13:13.605 --> 13:18.702
And the liani is a semidomesticated
plant found in the western amazon basin.

13:18.808 --> 13:22.302
Scientific name -
banisteriopsis caapi malpighiaceae.

13:22.408 --> 13:26.300
Known locally in Quichua as ayahuasca,
or vine of the soul.

13:26.405 --> 13:31.002
This name is given to the plant
by the indigenous people because of
its effectiveness in healing wounds.

13:31.106 --> 13:34.403
We harvested several samples
in the urubamba river drainage.

13:34.506 --> 13:37.102
In this same area,
we took samples of kemishitsa,

13:37.206 --> 13:40.001
a very powerful hallucinogenic.

13:40.108 --> 13:42.202
The plant research we're doing
will help find treatments

13:42.306 --> 13:46.003
and hopefully cures for some of
humanity's most virulent diseases -

13:46.105 --> 13:52.501
marburg, lassa fever, ebola, yellow
fever, dengue fever, and the diseases.

13:54.508 --> 13:58.303
The hemorrhagic fevers that...

14:08.506 --> 14:13.100
I'm... I'm sorry.
I don't know what's wrong.

14:19.607 --> 14:24.701
We'll have to continue this
another time. I'm sorry.

14:32.107 --> 14:34.100
Dr Grogan, please,
I need to talk to you.

14:34.207 --> 14:35.402
Not right now, please.

14:35.507 --> 14:38.903
- It will only take a few minutes.
- Not right now, please.

14:39.006 --> 14:41.700
Are you ok?

15:02.107 --> 15:03.901
You surprise me!

15:04.005 --> 15:06.000
I saw you in that lecture,
and I thought to myself,

15:06.107 --> 15:10.103
"what interest could she possibly
have in medicinal jungle plants?"

15:10.208 --> 15:11.600
I like flowers.

15:11.705 --> 15:13.402
Really?
Anything in particular?

15:13.507 --> 15:15.600
Una de Gato. What about you?
What flowers do you like?

15:15.708 --> 15:18.402
I don't. I was there for dr. Grogan.
She's a friend.

15:18.508 --> 15:19.200
Is she ok?

15:19.308 --> 15:21.500
Well, she's going through some
personal issues right now, getting

15:21.605 --> 15:24.200
a lot of pressure from the university.
It's very difficult being the top

15:24.305 --> 15:27.101
in one's field, as I very well know.

15:27.207 --> 15:29.003
I thought you said
this was about flowers.

15:29.108 --> 15:34.402
I just want to know
if someone died on that expedition.

15:34.508 --> 15:37.403
Martin Schaer was one of
our premier research scientists.

15:37.507 --> 15:40.403
Great writer.
He wrote a brilliant book.

15:40.508 --> 15:42.201
I have it here somewhere.
Let me tell you something.

15:42.306 --> 15:45.301
This guy had it all. He had
the charisma, the brains, the smarts.

15:45.406 --> 15:47.402
Great writer, brilliant professor.
I know what you're thinking.

15:47.508 --> 15:49.401
"Hey, that sounds a lot
like professor Rick Payne."

15:49.506 --> 15:52.102
But seriously, he was...
he was truly one of the greats.

15:52.207 --> 15:54.403
That's... that's Marty right there.

15:54.506 --> 15:56.301
He was a heck of a racquetball player, too.

15:56.407 --> 15:59.501
He beat me almost every week, and
I'm not easy to beat at racquetball.

15:59.607 --> 16:00.903
I'm good at racquetball.

16:01.005 --> 16:04.302
Even had a couple species of
jungle plants named after him.
Did you know that?

16:04.408 --> 16:05.603
You knew him well?

16:05.707 --> 16:06.400
Oh, yeah.

16:06.505 --> 16:08.103
Whenever he'd go on
one of his expeditions,

16:08.207 --> 16:10.500
he would always come back
with something for my collection,

16:10.606 --> 16:11.900
as you can see.

16:12.008 --> 16:15.500
He died on this expedition,
and not...

16:15.607 --> 16:16.903
not in a good way.

16:17.008 --> 16:19.101
Dr. Grogan was on
that same expedition.

16:19.206 --> 16:21.601
Made her famous. She got
all the accolades and awards,

16:21.708 --> 16:23.403
all the kudos
they could throw at her.

16:23.508 --> 16:24.803
A lot of people think
she didn't deserve it.

16:24.906 --> 16:28.601
It was actually Martin Schaer
who was the driving force
behind that expedition

16:28.706 --> 16:30.900
and  she was taking advantage of
his death because he was her mentor,

16:31.006 --> 16:33.203
but either way you look at it,
he's dead, she's not.

16:33.305 --> 16:35.703
She looks great in a pair of shorts, 
and she's got brains and talent,

16:35.808 --> 16:38.103
and when you look like she does
and you can go into the jungle

16:38.205 --> 16:40.803
and hang out with guys that
sharpen their teeth with files,

16:40.905 --> 16:42.703
you're gonna get a lot of attention.

16:42.808 --> 16:44.903
And whenever I see dr Grogan,
I think to myself,

16:45.005 --> 16:48.502
"Wow. Has she got a body or what?"

16:48.608 --> 16:51.303
Do you have to be this crass,
or can't you help it?

16:51.405 --> 16:55.900
I can help it. I usually do it
as a defense mechanism so I don't get
too emotionally attached to humanity.

16:56.005 --> 17:00.201
You might have to be
a different person with your wife.

17:00.308 --> 17:03.903
With  her, I don't have to be
so charming.

17:04.007 --> 17:06.502
Where's that book?
"Cat's Claw."

17:06.608 --> 17:10.301
It was right... here.
"Cat's claw" was the name of it.

17:10.407 --> 17:12.300
- Do you see it?
- Maybe somebody borrowed it.

17:12.507 --> 17:14.400
No, if they borrowed it,
I would know. It's my book.

17:14.508 --> 17:17.000
I would know if it was... borrowed.

17:17.105 --> 17:20.401
- Can I buy a copy?
- Yeah, at the university bookstore.

17:20.505 --> 17:21.803
- Sorry.
- Ok.

17:21.905 --> 17:24.101
Wait. Why are so you so interested
in this all of a sudden?

17:24.208 --> 17:25.300
Why... what's going on?

17:25.405 --> 17:27.400
Do you think Grogan had something
to do with Marty's death?

17:27.507 --> 17:28.301
I don't know yet.

17:28.407 --> 17:30.601
Well, why were you at the lecture?
What were you gonna ask Grogan?

17:30.706 --> 17:32.103
I need to read the book first.

17:32.205 --> 17:34.803
You're talking in circles.
You know I know you're not being
straight with me, right?

17:34.906 --> 17:36.300
- How would I know that?
- You're doing it again!

17:36.405 --> 17:38.201
You don't think I know a circle-talker
when I meet one?

17:38.305 --> 17:40.102
I don't think you'd find
my ideas very interesting.

17:40.208 --> 17:43.103
Hey, don't prejudge. Just because
I'm rude, snide, and sarcastic

17:43.208 --> 17:44.702
doesn't mean I don't have
a sensitive side.

17:44.806 --> 17:49.302
If you do see something strange,
call me.

18:00.506 --> 18:03.400
Son of a bitch.

18:06.805 --> 18:09.703
Where were you?

18:29.407 --> 18:31.903
Damn it!

18:46.206 --> 18:49.302
All right. Come on!

19:16.207 --> 19:18.603
You cannot believe the things
this guy has done.

19:18.706 --> 19:21.203
I mean, the places he's been,
just looking for plants.

19:21.307 --> 19:22.101
Get this:

19:22.208 --> 19:26.203
He was held for 10 days by drug dealers
in the rainforest of Venezuela.

19:26.308 --> 19:28.003
The guy's Indiana Jones.

19:28.106 --> 19:29.300
You know?

19:29.408 --> 19:31.000
He's the guy every guy wants to be.

19:31.105 --> 19:32.303
And he's dead.

19:32.408 --> 19:34.800
Well, yeah, except for that part.

19:34.905 --> 19:38.403
He got his ph. D. when he was 22,
then he spent the next 13 years

19:38.506 --> 19:41.603
teaching at the university and going on
expeditions for months at a time

19:41.705 --> 19:43.401
looking for cures to disease.

